Folder 3. Bromus pinnatus [TA]. i. Cites Linn. Sp. Pl; Huds. Fl. Angl; Ray's Syn. 392. 
 ii. "This Grass has all the characteristic Marks of a Festuca, tho' it has the. Face & Habit of a Bromus. It differs from the Festuca sylvatica of Hudson only in having smooth spiculae, & very short Aristae or acumina, which do not seem to be Marks sufficiently constant to distinguish it as a Species. It is found now & then in dry stiff ground, by Roadsides & Hedges. I gathered these Samples in Glocestershire near Highnam, two Miles from Gloucester in the Road to Newent, growing with the Festuca Sylvatica of Hudson. August" [JL]. 
 iii. "Q;

Sheet 1\. Juncus bulbosus TA. i.
This Juncus has deceiv'd a friend of mine very much, he took a large Flat of Ground by the Sea side w*^ he thought was exceeding rich Soil but when Summer came it grew nothing but this Rush. Ne 15." [?];
"This is certainly the Juncus bulbosus Lin: as appears from Morison's but quoted by him, & in all probability the J: parvus cum pericarpiis [on reverse:] rotundis of Ray's Syn: 433 tho' falsely placed by Hudson under his J: acutus as a Var: This last Name of Ray is plac'd by Lin: under his J: bulbosus" JL.
